The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Slumdogged
                                                                                                               Slumdogged
                                          
	His Oscar-winning film ran to packed houses. Today, Slumdog Millionaire child actor Azharuddin Mohammed Ismail was without a house.        
	The 10-year-olds shanty in Bandras Garib Nagar slum was torn down along with 30 others in a pre-monsoon drive to remove illegal settlements that block drainage and cause waterlogging.        
	BMC assistant commissioner Umashankar Mistry, who led the crackdown, claimed he was unaware of Slumdog children living in the area.         
	Azhars mother Shameem was livid. They came when my son was sleeping and threw us out.        
	But the child star, who was seen cycling through the slum (in Fotocorp picture), showed didnt seem to care. We will wait for a few days and then rebuild the house. There is no point protesting. We will continue staying the way we used to, he said, sounding quite upbeat.        
	Azhars co-star and neighbour Rubina Ali was lucky: her shanty has been spared as it does not block drainage.        
	Both their families may get flats in a low-price housing scheme of the state-run MHADA. State Congress chief Kripa Shankar Singh had put in such a request before chief minister Ashok Chavan a few months ago.                    OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                                                                                                                                                                   
